WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.560
Hello, everybody.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:11.280
My name is Ellis Hughes, and as you can tell probably from this title slide here, I work

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:12.280
at GSK.

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:17.360
I'm a data science leader in the Statistical Data Sciences and Innovation Hub, same as

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:24.000
Becca, who presented earlier, and we're responsible for innovation and developing of our packages

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:25.680
to try to improve processes and whatnot.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:29.200
So I thought I'd come here today to talk about that a little bit.

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:35.320
So I think, sorry, I think we've all worked on a process before that promised the world

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:41.119
that it was supposed to solve all our problems, make our lives substantially easier, and it

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:42.119
didn't do that.

00:00:42.119 --> 00:00:43.119
In fact, it made it harder.

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:44.119
It made it tougher.

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:45.119
It made it slower.

00:00:45.119 --> 00:00:50.119
You were confused the entire time, and I call those Edsels.

00:00:50.119 --> 00:00:52.160
Do you know what an Edsel is?

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:56.680
The Edsel is the automotive world's biggest flop.

00:00:56.680 --> 00:01:00.160
So I'm going to tell you a little bit of a story about the Edsel.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:04.879
So in 1957, Ford is hinting about the next car that they're going to be producing.

00:01:04.879 --> 00:01:07.720
The car of the future, it's going to be.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:16.040
They've spent 10 years developing this thing, $250 million of 1950s money, which is $2.5

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:21.639
billion today, and it's supposed to be this fantastical thing that's going to take us

00:01:21.639 --> 00:01:25.760
all into the future, and it's going to be full of technologies that are going to make

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:26.839
our lives easier.

00:01:26.839 --> 00:01:33.400
In 1958, the Edsel arrives with a lot of fanfare.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:37.559
They've got advertisements all over the world or all over the states.

00:01:37.559 --> 00:01:43.440
They've got a TV show about the Edsel, a TV show about the Edsel, of all things, and it's

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:45.599
got all this wonderful technology.

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:48.680
Like in your steering wheel, you can select your gear.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:50.000
You don't have to gear shift.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:51.000
It's just in your steering wheel.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.400
It's right there for you.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:58.519
On the dashboard, there's a button that squirts oil on your front suspension to keep it from

00:01:58.519 --> 00:01:59.519
squeaking.

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:01.959
Isn't that amazing?

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:04.120
But in 1959, they kill it.

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:05.120
It's done.

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:06.839
It's no longer out there anymore.

00:02:06.839 --> 00:02:10.080
In 1960, the last Edsel rolls off the line.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:14.479
This is a screen capture from a Times magazine where it's the wrong car, the wrong place,

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:15.720
the wrong time.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.600
But what happened from 1957, where it's the car of the future, supposed to be doing everything

00:02:20.839 --> 00:02:27.639
for us, to 1959, it's dead, it's gone, stop asking about it.

00:02:27.639 --> 00:02:30.919
Well, there are a couple different problems with the Edsel.

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:33.600
First, Edsel was designed by a committee.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:38.039
There was no real why driving the development of the Edsel, other than it's the car of the

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:39.039
future.

00:02:39.039 --> 00:02:40.039
It's got to have everything.

00:02:40.039 --> 00:02:42.199
It's going to be fantastic.

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:45.919
During this time, also, Ford was going through some restructuring, some changing, and so

00:02:45.919 --> 00:02:48.520
a lot of different executives were in charge of this project.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:51.679
Over the ten years, it was being developed, of course.

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:56.279
So they all wanted to put their thumbprint on the Edsel to enable to, you know, push

00:02:56.279 --> 00:03:00.279
their careers forward without really paying respect to what is this supposed to be?

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:03.080
What are we trying to actually accomplish here?

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:05.759
And then as I alluded to earlier, ten years of development.

00:03:05.759 --> 00:03:08.759
So when it was first released, they were all in on this.

00:03:08.759 --> 00:03:14.279
There were 18 different models that were available for people, not including colors, internal

00:03:14.279 --> 00:03:15.839
trims, all those other things.

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:20.240
This was just all the models that were available for the Edsel.

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:25.039
Then going on the idea of there was no real why behind it, there were no real requirements

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:27.839
or constraints when they were designing it.

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:32.119
So the car design, the horseshoe that you saw at the front there, was thought to be

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:36.160
really ugly, and in fact, people didn't like the way that it looked.

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:39.639
Now I don't really think it looks too bad, but, you know, whatever.

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:44.360
And then they also had a bunch of technology that didn't really solve any problems for

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:45.360
us.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:49.080
There were a bunch of technological solutions that were searching for a problem.

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:50.559
They're trying to identify that.

00:03:50.559 --> 00:03:53.240
You know those automatic gear shift selector in the steering wheel?

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:54.240
People hated it.

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.039
You know what you're used to in the center of your steering wheel?

00:03:56.039 --> 00:03:57.039
A horn.

00:03:57.039 --> 00:04:02.199
They'd hit the horn and they'd accidentally change gears.

00:04:02.199 --> 00:04:06.039
In addition, there was a lot of QA and QC issues related to all those technological

00:04:06.039 --> 00:04:07.039
solutions.

00:04:07.039 --> 00:04:10.199
They weren't really meant to be in production that early.

00:04:10.199 --> 00:04:16.359
And that led to issues where the factory was sending incomplete cars to their dealerships

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:20.440
with just all the different pieces that they didn't complete just sitting in the boot,

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:23.519
waiting for the dealerships to sort this out.

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:28.279
And so that's why, of many other reasons, the Edsel failed.

00:04:28.279 --> 00:04:32.679
But how can we take lessons from this and keep our next project from becoming the next

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:33.679
Edsel?

00:04:33.679 --> 00:04:39.799
So I'm going to go through a little case study of a project that we worked on where we identified

00:04:39.799 --> 00:04:43.320
a slow process that we wanted to fix.

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:50.279
So inside of our organization, we have a programming team that does all our data analysis and data

00:04:50.279 --> 00:04:51.279
prep.

00:04:51.279 --> 00:04:56.239
They process this data, they do all this formatting, and they've output to several different files

00:04:56.239 --> 00:05:01.799
and intending for downstream users to use this to generate reports and presentations

00:05:01.799 --> 00:05:04.359
and reports and whatnot.

00:05:04.359 --> 00:05:10.640
These downstream users take this, the statisticians will generate reports or presentations, and

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:15.760
our medical writers will generate reports of differing levels of programming backgrounds

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:16.760
and whatnot.

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:22.000
The issue with this is our programmers are generating data in formats that our downstream

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.440
users couldn't use directly.

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:28.279
That meant that there was a lot of manual reproducing of data, a lot of copy and paste

00:05:28.279 --> 00:05:34.399
from the format that we were producing into their PowerPoint and Word documents.

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:37.119
When people are copying and pasting, that leads to formatting inconsistencies.

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:41.399
They're like, oh, I'll just delete that, I don't like the way that percent looks, I'll

00:05:41.399 --> 00:05:46.200
just put it at the top there, or I want more spacing here, I want to merge these columns.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:49.720
Not fundamentally changing the data, but the way it's displayed.

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:53.359
And because we're doing all this copying and pasting and reformatting, we have to do a

00:05:53.359 --> 00:05:58.480
lot of really intense QC on data we've already generated and already QC'd to make sure that

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:01.720
we're not showing anything that's incorrect.

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:06.600
So there's all this effort going into this process that is just we're not producing the

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:10.480
correct data, we're not working, we're not talking together to make sure that everything

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:12.760
works together nicely.

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:15.839
But we saw this as, you know what, that's not a bad thing.

00:06:15.839 --> 00:06:19.920
That's an opportunity for us to step in and help and try to improve the process.

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:24.200
Because the data is being used by the same downstream user, or the same data are being

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:28.920
used by the downstream users, we can use this as a starting point and try to build processes

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:32.239
and build a package to try to make their lives easier.

00:06:32.239 --> 00:06:37.720
Next, we found out and learned about packages that have come out like the Officeverse, which

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:42.200
is a series of packages by David Goel that interact with Office products and help you

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:48.239
write your OOXML to allow you to inject and work with your Word and PowerPoint package

00:06:48.239 --> 00:06:50.559
or presentations and documents and whatnot.

00:06:50.559 --> 00:06:51.559
So Officer.

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:57.880
And there's also FlexTable, which is a package that helps you make tables into PowerPoints

00:06:57.880 --> 00:06:58.880
and Word documents.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:02.679
Kind of seems like it will be pretty useful for us.

00:07:02.679 --> 00:07:07.320
So before we really went and just went all full tilt to develop anything, we wanted to

00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:10.720
make sure we had a full set of expectations so we understood what we were trying to build

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:12.920
before we went to go build it.

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:15.880
So if we're designing a new workflow, we want to create collaboration.

00:07:16.399 --> 00:07:19.600
That was what was causing problems before between our programmers, statisticians, and

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:20.600
medical writers.

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:23.140
We wanted to work with our existing systems.

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:27.119
We don't want to have to try to create and roll up a new system.

00:07:27.119 --> 00:07:29.640
What do we have that what can we reuse?

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:31.559
Where can we extract the data from?

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:34.559
Can we pull from existing streams?

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:37.880
We're already using PowerPoint and DocX, so let's output to that.

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:41.359
Let's not make our end users relearn everything.

00:07:41.359 --> 00:07:45.239
And then as we generate these inputs, let's automatically tag those, because you can use

00:07:45.239 --> 00:07:50.040
comments in PowerPoint and DocX, tag those with comments that, hey, you're going to need

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:51.040
to QC this.

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:53.760
This was generated, you know, custom.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:56.920
And then ultimately this process originally was very slow.

00:07:56.920 --> 00:08:02.040
We wanted to reduce the timeline into less than a week.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:07.079
Then as we went to go develop the team, now that we had our expectations, we had a small

00:08:07.079 --> 00:08:11.559
team of experienced individuals that were both understood the process, what they were

00:08:11.559 --> 00:08:17.200
trying to replace, as well as understood what they were generating or how to program.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:18.200
This was important.

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:19.600
So we understood what were the constraints.

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:23.079
What could we feasibly make or not make?

00:08:23.079 --> 00:08:24.799
We had a single point decision maker.

00:08:24.799 --> 00:08:28.320
They were ultimately responsible for making a call if there was a disagreement.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:31.839
Then we worked with the experts, the people that we're using, our downstream users as

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:36.219
well as upstream users, to define, okay, what are the core things that we need to create?

00:08:36.359 --> 00:08:38.419
What are the features that need to be on the roadmap eventually?

00:08:38.419 --> 00:08:41.340
We maybe don't need them immediately.

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:43.419
But ultimately they did not have the final decision.

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:46.020
They weren't the executives at Ford that were telling us what to do.

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:49.780
They were saying, hey, it would be really nice if.

00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:51.260
We tried to simplify things.

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:53.059
We didn't want to try to recreate the wheel.

00:08:53.059 --> 00:08:55.460
Like I said, we didn't want to recreate systems.

00:08:55.460 --> 00:08:57.020
So let's use existing tools.

00:08:57.020 --> 00:09:01.099
Let's use Office first rather than trying to make our home cooked version of Office

00:09:01.099 --> 00:09:06.140
first to interact with the XML and PowerPoint and DocX.

00:09:06.659 --> 00:09:11.780
Let's use the tools that already exist and try to maybe improve it as we need to.

00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:14.940
People were adding their own standards and their own changes to the outputs.

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:17.619
So let's revert back to what are the standards?

00:09:17.619 --> 00:09:21.619
What exactly is it that we have to make and then we can maybe iterate from there?

00:09:21.619 --> 00:09:24.099
And then identify areas of common rework by the staff.

00:09:24.099 --> 00:09:26.820
What are the common reformatting that is being done?

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:28.340
And can we do this programmatically?

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:30.260
Is it reasonable to do it programmatically?

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:36.299
What are things that we need to capitalize or lowercase or change?

00:09:36.299 --> 00:09:39.619
While we developed this, too, we wanted to watch our scope.

00:09:39.619 --> 00:09:43.940
So we wanted to make sure that the system could grow as we need it to change as we need

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:44.940
it.

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:46.419
The world is a changing place.

00:09:46.419 --> 00:09:48.340
Let's try to keep that in mind.

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:52.380
The feature requests that we got, we would compare them against the feasibility of doing

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:53.380
that.

00:09:53.380 --> 00:09:54.580
Once again, can we do this programmatically?

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:59.299
Should we be doing this programmatically or should we push back and go, maybe this isn't

00:09:59.299 --> 00:10:00.820
the time?

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:02.140
We also have limited resources.

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:04.700
We had a small team of people working on this.

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:09.739
So that made us keep in mind that everything that we did was in strict adherence to the

00:10:09.739 --> 00:10:10.739
goals.

00:10:10.739 --> 00:10:13.419
What are we actually trying to achieve and try to push away things?

00:10:13.419 --> 00:10:14.419
This might sound a little bit familiar.

00:10:14.419 --> 00:10:15.419
This is kind of agile.

00:10:15.419 --> 00:10:18.419
I don't know if you've ever heard of that.

00:10:18.419 --> 00:10:21.299
It's pretty popular.

00:10:21.299 --> 00:10:25.820
So I'm happy to report that this actually, this project did turn out pretty well.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:28.099
We've reduced the reporting time significantly.

00:10:28.619 --> 00:10:32.460
We've been able to generate reports in under a week.

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:35.820
There's no programming skills required by our non-programming staff.

00:10:35.820 --> 00:10:38.739
They are not required to write any programming.

00:10:38.739 --> 00:10:44.700
We're able to generate their reports using the programmers and then just running it through

00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:51.340
this tool that we've created, and as everyone asks in pharma, it is validated.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:54.739
Per our internal process.

00:10:54.739 --> 00:10:59.739
So the reason this project succeeded, I believe, I've named a couple of those as well, we established

00:10:59.739 --> 00:11:00.739
our requirements.

00:11:00.739 --> 00:11:01.739
We knew what our outputs were.

00:11:01.739 --> 00:11:05.419
We knew what we were trying to create, and we didn't deviate from that.

00:11:05.419 --> 00:11:07.140
We knew what our measurement of success was.

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:13.140
We knew if we achieved this goal, we succeeded, and anything that we did was only in trying

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:16.140
to achieve that goal.

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:17.479
We were relentless.

00:11:17.479 --> 00:11:21.099
When people asked us to add new features, we'd go, okay, do you need this now or is

00:11:21.099 --> 00:11:23.340
this something that can happen later?

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:27.260
We kept perspective of the values that we were adding and tried, once again, it's all

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:30.140
about not doing things we don't need to do.

00:11:30.140 --> 00:11:33.619
Don't add unnecessary things unless you need to.

00:11:33.619 --> 00:11:35.580
And then also single point decision making.

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:38.940
Ultimately, one person had to make a call.

00:11:38.940 --> 00:11:39.940
Okay.

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:46.900
I'm going to close with a final story from the same company, Ford, and we're going to

00:11:46.900 --> 00:11:53.020
make a GT, not an Edsel.

00:11:53.700 --> 00:12:01.659
So 1966, Ford wins the world-renowned hardest race in the racing world, the 24 hours of

00:12:01.659 --> 00:12:05.859
Le Mans, which is a race where people drive for 24 hours and the winner is determined

00:12:05.859 --> 00:12:08.700
not by how many laps they do, but how far they drive.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:12.940
This is a true endurance test of the quality of your car, how good is it made, how well

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:15.179
did you design this?

00:12:15.179 --> 00:12:21.580
The impressive thing about this, this is the second year Ford had ever competed in Le Mans.

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:25.419
They'd never competed in it before.

00:12:25.419 --> 00:12:29.739
The prior winner had been Ferrari, who'd won for the last six years and has a long history

00:12:29.739 --> 00:12:31.419
in racing.

00:12:31.419 --> 00:12:38.780
So how did Ford go from a company that made a thing like the Edsel to the GT and won the

00:12:38.780 --> 00:12:42.780
whole darn thing in their second year of competing?

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:46.299
Well, they had a small dedicated team.

00:12:46.299 --> 00:12:48.859
They set out to beat Ferrari.

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:50.539
That was their goal in mind.

00:12:50.539 --> 00:12:55.340
Not just win the 24 hours of Le Mans, but let's beat Ferrari.

00:12:55.340 --> 00:13:02.299
They got together a small team, Carroll Shelby and Ken Miles, who had a history of success

00:13:02.299 --> 00:13:03.979
doing this sort of thing.

00:13:03.979 --> 00:13:08.619
Carroll Shelby was an old racer, so he used to race, he actually won Le Mans I think a

00:13:08.619 --> 00:13:12.659
decade or two before and started his own car company called Shelby American.

00:13:12.659 --> 00:13:15.580
You might know him from the Shelby Cobra.

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:22.380
As well as Ken Miles, who had been a successful driver in Britain, racing various cars of

00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:24.539
various degrees.

00:13:24.539 --> 00:13:29.500
And then everything they did for the next two years was focused on results.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:31.780
What could they do to make the GT faster?

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:34.380
How could they win Le Mans?

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:37.260
They've worked through aerodynamics.

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:39.340
They had an initial concept.

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:42.099
They did, they constantly drove around.

00:13:42.099 --> 00:13:44.900
They had their drivers that were going to be in the race drive the car around, give

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:46.900
feedback to the engineers.

00:13:46.900 --> 00:13:51.580
Even this is a picture of the engineers and drivers with little pieces of string that

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:57.500
they taped onto the GT to see how aerodynamics worked and if there were any areas of low

00:13:57.500 --> 00:14:00.059
pressure that they would need to address.

00:14:00.059 --> 00:14:02.619
And they trusted the driver's experience.

00:14:02.619 --> 00:14:04.700
In addition to that, they pushed technologies forward.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:09.020
They took the Ford's proven racing engine from NASCAR and improved it.

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:11.179
They made it faster, they made it stronger.

00:14:11.179 --> 00:14:13.900
They took existing technologies and made it better.

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:15.260
And they also innovated.

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:19.979
They took the quick change or they invented a quick change brake pads and rotors.

00:14:19.979 --> 00:14:21.340
The GT was a very heavy car.

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:25.099
They brake a lot in Le Mans or they have to press the brake pad.

00:14:25.099 --> 00:14:27.380
So they needed a quick way to redo this.

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:30.659
So they created new technologies in order to solve the problems at hand.

00:14:30.659 --> 00:14:32.260
And that was all they were ever focused on.

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:33.260
How can we do this faster?

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:34.260
How can we do this better?

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:38.260
So I'm going to end with this.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:41.299
Projects and packages should be designed with purpose and be relentless in pursuing their

00:14:41.299 --> 00:14:42.299
goals.

00:14:42.299 --> 00:14:44.140
And that's how you make a good packaging process.

00:14:44.140 --> 00:14:45.380
Thank you.

